WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:03.000
I'd like to introduce Allaire here.

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Thanks. Thank you very much.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:08.000
And thanks everybody for coming.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
I'm here today to talk about publishing Jupyter Notebooks with Quarto.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:15.000
I'm J.J. Allaire. I'm from POSIT.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Tracy will be in front. Just for Tracy. She's from POSIT.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:20.000
POSIT used to be called RStudio.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:22.000
So you may not have heard of POSIT.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:24.000
It was probably the name of RStudio.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:27.000
So, we're going to talk a lot about Quarto today.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:29.000
But before we talk about Quarto,

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
I want to talk at a very high level about Jupyter Notebooks

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:35.000
and what is special about them.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:38.000
And for those of you who are users of Jupyter Notebooks

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.000
or curious about Jupyter Notebooks,

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.000
passionate about Jupyter Notebooks,

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:46.000
I really strongly recommend you read this paper

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:49.000
that was written by Brian Granger and Fernando Perez

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:51.000
who actually created Jupyter Notebooks.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.000
And they talk about what's special and distinctive about Jupyter Notebooks.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:57.000
And of course, as we all know,

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.000
and we all probably benefit from all the time,

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Jupyter Notebooks are an interactive computing environment.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.000
But more than that, they, you know, my emphasis here,

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:12.000
help humans to think and tell stories with code and data.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Jupyter Notebooks' narrative and writing

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.000
are a fundamental part of using a Jupyter Notebook.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
And it really is important in two dimensions.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
How many of us have, when writing about how we're going to solve a problem,

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:26.000
that actually affects how we solve the problem.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:28.000
Or writing about what we're going to do in the code

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.000
actually affects what we do in the code.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
And how many of us have produced output,

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:38.000
a visualization, a model result, various figures,

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.000
but there's additional context required to understand what we produced.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.000
And that's the telling stories part.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.000
So reflecting a little more about this idea of telling stories

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.000
and telling the whole stories,

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
some of you may have read Edward Tufte's pamphlet,

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
which is sort of a takedown of the reductive style of PowerPoint

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:04.000
for communicating about data specifically.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
He has a bunch of examples in the pamphlet.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:11.000
One of them specifically actually has the PowerPoint deck

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.000
that was used to greenlight the ill-fated space shuttle launch.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And some of the figures they presented were very much presented in isolation

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
with some very, very short bullets on a slide.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:25.000
And there's actually quite a bit of important context

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:27.000
that was needed to understand those figures.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:31.000
So he's urging us to do more when we communicate about data.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:35.000
Actually, a podcast that I just heard the other day

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:37.000
was an interview with Bill James.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:39.000
How many of you here have heard of Bill James?

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.000
So you've probably heard of the movie Moneyball.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:44.000
And Bill James was actually the person

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.000
who kind of started the revolution that led to Moneyball.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:50.000
And anyway, he kind of invented sort of this idea

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:54.000
of deep data analysis of baseball and sports.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:57.000
But he's actually, as things have gone on,

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.000
become kind of disillusioned with where that movement has gone

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:02.000
because it's also become quite reductive,

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:04.000
where people are obsessed with producing a single number,

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.000
wins above replacement,

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:09.000
that fully encapsulates the value of a baseball player.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:13.000
And when he used to write and do data analysis about baseball,

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.000
he had quite a bit of narrative that went along with it.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.000
So this idea of narrative that describe our assumptions,

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.000
constraints, qualifications, that go along with the data

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.000
and visualizations that we present

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:26.000
is really fundamentally important.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.000
And that's this idea of telling stories,

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.000
computational narratives, telling stories about data.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:33.000
And that's kind of where Jupyter fits,

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
and also, as you'll see in this talk, Cordo fits.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
So before I get into some of the specifics,

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.000
I want to acknowledge there's quite a bit of history

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.000
in this building tools to help people

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.000
with sophisticated technical narratives,

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
interactive computing, weaving those together.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
That goes back to tech, but it also goes back to notebooks,

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
various implementations of Markdown, Jupyter itself.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:59.000
And all these tools have kind of, I think,

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:03.000
really weaved themselves together in recent years

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
to create a very compelling environment

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
for computational narratives and storytelling of data.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:11.000
On to Cordo.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
I spend most of my time now working on Cordo,

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.000
but prior to that, I worked on the RStudio IDE

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.000
along with Joe Cheng, who's here, I think,

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
and who you probably heard, some of you may have heard

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
get a talk about Shiny for Python yesterday.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:27.000
So I worked on RStudio IDE.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.000
I worked on RMarkdown, which was a predecessor to Cordo

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.000
that was R-specific.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
And I also worked on the R interface to Python

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:37.000
and the R interfaces to a bunch of other

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:41.000
machine learning distributed computing libraries.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
And I worked on RMarkdown for a long time,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
and I became very convinced that the ideas behind it

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.000
were sound and valuable,

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:51.000
and customers were getting a lot of value out of it.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:53.000
But I was discouraged by the fact that it was really

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:56.000
only a small slice of the people that could benefit from it

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
because it was R-specific.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:00.000
And so I've actually spent the last few years

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:02.000
focusing on a new project, Cordo,

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:04.000
which is an open source project.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.000
It's kind of a ground-up rewrite

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:09.000
of some of the things we did in RMarkdown,

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:12.000
but it's multi-language and multi-engine.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
So we'll see this diagram a couple times in this talk,

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
and we'll go into different levels of depth about it,

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
but I want to give you a really, really high level.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:22.000
What is Cordo?

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
It's taking computations and narrative

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:27.000
from Jupyter Notebook.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
It's Markdown plus the code and whatever it produced.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.000
That all goes into Markdown,

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:37.000
and then it's transformed by a tool called Pandoc,

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:38.000
which we'll talk about a little bit more.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.000
It's a Markdown rendering engine,

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:41.000
into lots of different types of output.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.000
That's kind of the core mechanic,

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.000
and we'll drill into more depth at these different steps

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
and what's important and how you can customize it

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
and hack the system.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:55.000
So the core roadmap for what I want to cover in today's talk,

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:57.000
I want to talk a little bit more about

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.000
supporting the idea of computational narratives,

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.000
talk a little bit about the specific requirements

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.000
around technical communications.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.000
This is distinct from writing in Gmail or writing in Google Doc.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
We deal with lots of special types of content and assets

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.000
when we do technical communication.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:17.000
This idea of semantic authoring,

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:20.000
where we can write once and publish in many places.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
A little bit more getting into notebooks,

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.000
the pros and cons and different uses

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
and ways they can be melded and tooled.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:31.000
And then a little more about how the system works

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:33.000
and how you can hack and extend it

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.000
and make it do exactly what you want it to do.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:40.000
So first, how do we support computational narratives?

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
Well, the core requirements,

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
it's kind of what I just described.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.000
You've got to be able to render executable content from Jupyter.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:47.000
You've got to be able to include

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:49.000
these kind of technical content types.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.000
You've got to be able to then take Markdown

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.000
and turn it into a lot of different output formats.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
This is, you know, Porto does this,

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.000
but it's not the first tool to do it.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:01.000
In fact, there's a tool called MVConvert

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.000
that's been around since the dawn of Jupyter, I think,

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:05.000
that does this sort of thing.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:07.000
And then there's also a couple newer projects,

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:10.000
JupyterBook and Mist.js, that also do it.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
So this talk, I'm going to focus very much,

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
kind of talk about the tooling for computational narratives

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:15.000
through the lens of Porto,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:18.000
but it's important to know these other tools exist.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:19.000
They share a lot of the same features,

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.000
and they're definitely all worth taking a look at.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.000
So, how does Porto work?

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:27.000
You can see here at the command line,

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:28.000
where we have a notebook,

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
and we say, Porto, render the notebook,

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
and that kicks off this pipeline.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:35.000
The notebook may or may not have been executed.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:37.000
It could have been, you've already executed it

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.000
interactively in JupyterLab or VS Code,

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.000
or maybe that you'd like to fully re-execute it.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:45.000
I'll show you this in a minute.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.000
We're going to want to tailor the output

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:48.000
that we get out of the notebook

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
that goes into Word or a website or a PDF or a presentation.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
We do that by providing options.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:57.000
And then, what you see at the top,

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
once we have our notebook ready,

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
we just Porto render,

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
and we get the output that we're looking for.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
Just a little bit about Pandoc

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:07.000
before I get into a bunch of examples.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:09.000
Pandoc is really, by itself,

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
an extraordinary piece of software

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.000
that we're kind of building on top of,

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
and a lot of the reason why we're able to do,

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:16.000
implement a lot of the features

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
we're able to implement and support

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
all of the output formats we're able to support.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:23.000
It was actually created not quite almost 20 years ago,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:25.000
but over 15 years ago,

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:26.000
by John McFarlane,

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
who's also one of the folks who's behind CommonMark.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:31.000
Pandoc has CommonMark,

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:34.000
plus a lot of extensions for technical writing,

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
definition lists, citations,

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
more sophisticated tables, things like that.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:43.000
It supports dozens of output formats,

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:44.000
and I'll get into that later,

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
but just about any output format you can name

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:47.000
is supported by Pandoc.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
And most importantly, it's very extensible.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
You can write custom readers, custom writers.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:54.000
You can filter.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
The documents are read into an AST

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:57.000
that you can compute on.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:58.000
So it's a great foundation

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
for building a publishing platform.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:02.000
Okay, so let's start.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:03.000
Let's do a few examples,

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
and this example will not be terribly impressive.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:07.000
It's something you've seen before.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:08.000
We start with a Jupyter notebook.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:11.000
It's just printing a few rows from a table

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:13.000
and plotting, doing a plot.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:17.000
And we take that and we render it into a web page.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:18.000
You've seen this before.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
Again, nbconvert, lots of tools do this.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:21.000
Hopefully we made the web page

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:22.000
a little bit more attractive

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
than you might usually see,

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:27.000
but very straightforward transformation.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:28.000
You see all the code,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:29.000
and you see all the outputs.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:31.000
Okay, so now let's talk about

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:33.000
the different ways you might tailor

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:34.000
this output with options.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:36.000
Here we're actually gonna add

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
some document-level options.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
We're gonna change the theme,

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
the sort of theme of the output,

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
the kind of overall CSS template of the page.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:47.000
We're gonna change the code highlighting style,

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:50.000
and we're also gonna say that we want to

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
allow viewers of the document,

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:53.000
readers of the document,

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:55.000
to add comments to it using hypothesis.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
So when we take this notebook and we render it,

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
we see now it has a different look.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
The code is indeed highlighted

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:03.000
using a different highlight style,

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:04.000
and you can see on the far right

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.000
there's this commenting bar

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:07.000
that can be used for people

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:09.000
to make comments on the notebook.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:11.000
So those are document-level options.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
There's also cell-level options.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.000
So I want to focus on the cell-level options,

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:17.000
but also note we've added

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:19.000
some different document-level options.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:22.000
Here we've said we'd actually like to hide the code,

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:26.000
but make it folded so that users can see it if they want,

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:27.000
and we wanted to add some tools

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.000
for letting the users kind of globally enable

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.000
and disable source code.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
So that's some different global options

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:34.000
or document options.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
And then here we've said that we want to

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.000
provide a caption for our figure,

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:40.000
and we want to provide a label

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.000
so that we can cross-reference it.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:43.000
So now when we render this,

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:47.000
you can see the code is indeed collapsed, folded.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
There's this code menu up here

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.000
that we'll demonstrate in a minute,

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
and you can see that the figure does have a caption,

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
and it's cross-referencable.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:00.000
When I open that code menu and say show all code,

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
and you can see the code cells open.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
So these are just examples.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:05.000
There's actually, believe it or not,

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
hundreds of options that affect

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
how documents look and behave,

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
and dozens of options that affect

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
how computations are presented.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
It's extremely flexible and powerful.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:18.000
This is just an example of sort of

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:22.000
how you interact with all those capabilities.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
One of the things I want to emphasize is that,

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.000
again, you've seen NVConvert.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:27.000
Making a web page from a notebook

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:28.000
is not particularly impressive.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:29.000
GitHub does it, too,

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
when you view a notebook on GitHub.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
But our goal is to go well,

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
well beyond simple conversion,

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:37.000
and some of those options that I was showing you

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:38.000
hinted that.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
We want you to produce professional

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.000
production quality output in whatever format you need,

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
and complex outputs,

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:50.000
outputs like books, blogs, websites, presentations,

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
really nice printed documents.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
All those things is our goal with the tool,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
not just kicking out the web page.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
So a couple examples of this.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:04.000
Here I'm going to change the format to docx,

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:05.000
and now when I render,

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
I'm going to get a Word document.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:08.000
I've got an option that says

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:11.000
I want to put the two plots side by side.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
That would be a little annoying to do in Word,

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.000
and this just sort of does that automatically.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
So that's Word.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:24.000
We also have lots of tooling for creating PDFs.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:25.000
Here I'll show you,

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
we're going to use a bibliography.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:28.000
We're going to say

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
we actually want to put citations in the margin,

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:33.000
because the optimal reading width

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
is somewhere around like 600 pixels,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
and so on a printed page actually,

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
you actually have extra room in the margins to do things.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
We'll put the citations there,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
and then we'll also,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
we'll actually put our figures in two columns,

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.000
and we'll use the entire page,

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:50.000
again, using the margin.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:51.000
So you can see here,

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:54.000
I've got my optimal reading width,

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
I've got the citation and the margin,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
and then I'm using the entire width of the page for the plot.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
So lots of tools like this

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
to make very tailored, readable output.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:09.000
This presentation actually was created with Cordo.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
We can create PowerPoint decks,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:17.000
Beamer decks, and Reveal.js decks.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:18.000
This is Reveal.js.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
This is an example of creating slides,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:23.000
and here I've said I want to put a logo on my slides

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:26.000
and include a slide number in the upper right-hand corner.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
Here you can see now I've got a slide

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.000
that has the two plots, the logo and the numbers

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:34.000
that are indicated by the options.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:38.000
This is just showing a couple of plots.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:39.000
You might actually be trying to teach people

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:40.000
about how to code a plot.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
That's a common application.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
You're sort of doing an internal presentation,

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
trying to teach people how to use an API or a library.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:49.000
And so here, we're actually going to say,

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
echo true, meaning please show the code,

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.000
and we actually want to highlight specific line numbers

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
so that as we're talking through the code,

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.000
the audience can focus on the right thing at the right time.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
So here you can see we've got echo.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:02.000
The code is shown.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
Here, just line four is highlighted,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:06.000
and then when I advance the slide,

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
it's going to highlight line five.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
So this is a tool for sort of doing

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
technical explanations of code.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
And there's lots of other things related to code

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.000
and slides that support internal presentations.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:22.000
So far, I've just shown you single documents,

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.000
but Cordova also has a project system

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:28.000
for aggregating together multiple documents,

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:33.000
and that might be just sharing settings and assets like CSS,

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:37.000
or it might be to create a website or to create a book.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:38.000
That's the project system.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:42.000
So you can see here, I've got my Cordova project config file.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:43.000
I say it's a website.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.000
I provide some website options,

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.000
and then I say all the HTML that's in this website

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:51.000
should share this theme and these extra CSS styles.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
That's a really simple project.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:56.000
I'll show you some examples of some more sophisticated projects.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:59.000
This is at the website for the Fast AI,

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
a deep learning for coders course.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
Here you can see there's a little more going on.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.000
This is pretty similar, but here we've got some social links.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.000
We've got some tailoring how links to GitHub work,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
and you can see now this is a full website.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:16.000
So this is quite a few documents,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:19.000
maybe 20 different documents linked to the sidebar.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:22.000
You can also link to them in the nav bar and have the nav bar menu

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
or have a combination of those things.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
So this is a whole website done with Cordova,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
written, again, in notebooks.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:32.000
Here's a blog.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:35.000
Similar, we have some social stuff, Google Analytics,

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:38.000
a little bit in customizing the behavior of the nav bar

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
and when it collapses.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.000
Here the home page looks a little different.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.000
It sort of has tiles for all the different blog posts.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
So this is a blog done as a project.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
And then an example of a book.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.000
Here you can see, again, some similar options

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:57.000
related to the Git repo that is where the books develop,

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.000
but also here now we've actually indicated the chapters

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
and the order of the chapters.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
And then when we render the book, you can see we have the number of chapters.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:08.000
We actually have the number of sections and subsections,

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.000
and we actually can resolve cross-references across chapters.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
So one of the interesting things about books,

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:17.000
this book is a web-based version of the book,

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.000
but, obviously, it's not super helpful

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
if you actually want to print a book

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:25.000
or publish the book for Kindle or iBook users.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.000
So books actually are multi-format.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:34.000
So you can think of a book as a website that has extra features,

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.000
but you can also take that from the same notebooks

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:41.000
and produce a PDF book, a Word version of the book,

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.000
EPUB, or ASCII doc.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.000
And ASCII doc is actually the format that's used by O'Reilly for their books.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:52.000
So there's a bunch of people writing O'Reilly books using Cordo

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
and then just taking advantage of the ASCII doc output

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.000
and then feeding that to O'Reilly.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:00.000
Okay, let's talk a little bit about some of the specific requirements

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:04.000
of technical communication and how Cordo supports those.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:08.000
So what's different about technical communication?

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:12.000
I found this interesting that Google Docs now supports code blocks,

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:15.000
but that's as of, like, five months ago.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:19.000
So if you're doing technical communication,

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:21.000
you definitely want to be able to display code.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:24.000
So my point here is that tools like Microsoft Word and Google Docs

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:27.000
are not made for technical communication.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:30.000
Sophisticated presentation of source code,

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:34.000
citations and cross-references, math, diagrams,

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:37.000
lots of things you want to do that are not well-supported

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.000
by general-purpose tools.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:43.000
So how do we have support for these things?

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
I showed you earlier some of the things about code

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
and customizing the highlighting and making it hideable.

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:51.000
We've got some other things if you're trying to explain code

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:54.000
where if you've got, you know, here's a code block.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
I want to explain these three lines of code.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
I've got numbers next to them,

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:02.000
and then I've got narrative explaining each line of code below.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:06.000
And the way you do that is you have your line of code

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:07.000
you want to write narrative about,

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:10.000
you have a list below, and so on and so forth.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:11.000
So that's code annotation.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:13.000
There's lots and lots of tools for customizing

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:16.000
how source code is displayed.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:19.000
Diagrams, for those of you who haven't done this,

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:22.000
it's actually a pretty cool way to create diagrams.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
You can actually write diagrams in plain text.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
This is a mermaid diagram,

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:29.000
and in fact, GitHub now supports mermaid diagrams,

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
you know, in GitHub-flavored markdowns.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:34.000
So if you want to write a diagram as part of a pull request

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:38.000
or on an issue or in GitHub wiki, you can use mermaid.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:41.000
And then graph is an older text-based diagramming system

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
that's still in pretty wide use.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:47.000
So this code here that I put in a quarter document or a notebook

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
results in this diagram.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:52.000
So for those of you who have struggled with Visio

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:55.000
or tools like that to try to wrestle a diagram

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:56.000
into looking how you want,

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:59.000
this is actually a significantly easier way to do it.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:03.000
Equations, of course, lots of times you need to use equations

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:05.000
in technical communication,

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:08.000
and here's a couple examples of LaTeX equations.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
And then those get automatically converted.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:13.000
You know, for Word docs, those get converted into MathML.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:16.000
You know, for environments that understand LaTeX equations,

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
they state LaTeX equations.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:21.000
So those are supported for all output formats.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:24.000
I showed you a little bit before figures and cross-references.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:28.000
Here I'm going to show a figure that actually has a caption

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:31.000
that's a figure and two sub-figures.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
And to do that, I just say I've got a figure

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
and I've got two sub-captions.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:39.000
And when I render this notebook, you can see it's got the figure,

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.000
but it's also got two sub-figures,

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:45.000
and those are referenceable individually.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:48.000
And there's lots of ways to customize figure panels.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.000
You can have two, three.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:53.000
You can have two on top of two and two on top of one.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:57.000
Lots of different ways to customize how figures are displayed.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:59.000
I won't go into a lot of detail about this,

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:04.000
but there's quite deep support for citations and bibliographies

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
and lots of different output styles

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
and lots of different ways of presenting citations.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:11.000
So that's one of the most significant kind of extensions

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:13.000
to Common Mark that PANOC makes

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:15.000
is the ability to handle citations really well.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:18.000
And call-outs is another thing you see a lot in technical books

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.000
and technical communication.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:23.000
You can see different types of call-outs that, you know,

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:26.000
in some ways they can amplify the importance of content,

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:28.000
but sometimes they can indicate to the user

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.000
that you don't really need to read this

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:32.000
unless you're a specific type of reader,

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
and we support call-outs

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.000
for just about all the most interesting output formats

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:40.000
that are targeted by Core Data.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:43.000
I talked a little bit earlier about using the margins

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:45.000
because, again, the kind of optimum reading width

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:48.000
is not 800 or 1,000 pixels.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:51.000
And so you can actually put content in the margin.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:53.000
Here's an example of a notebook

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.000
where we put an equation in the margin

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:57.000
or even a figure or a table in the margin.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:59.000
It's useful because there's ancillary information

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:01.000
that you think the user might want to consult,

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.000
but you don't want to burden the main narrative with it.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:07.000
It's very easy to stick things into the margin.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:10.000
And here's an example of a visualization.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:13.000
It's, you know, it's a four-plot panel.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:16.000
It really wants to be as wide as possible.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:18.000
And so we're going to say use the entire screen

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:20.000
with a little bit of inset.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
So now I render this in a web page.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:24.000
No matter how big that web page gets,

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:26.000
it's going to use the full screen.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
So let's really make sure this visualization

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:30.000
is seen as large as possible.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:34.000
Lots of different options for how you use columns

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:37.000
with figures and other things.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:39.000
All right, a little bit more about this idea

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:41.000
of semantic authoring.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:43.000
What do I mean by semantic authoring?

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:45.000
Well, I'll define it a little bit by saying

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:47.000
what is literal authoring?

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.000
Literal authoring is writing or creating

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:51.000
technical content or report or analysis

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:54.000
kind of in the native format of a given medium.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:56.000
So I'm writing a dissertation in LaTeX.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:58.000
I'm creating a presentation with Keynote.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:00.000
I'm publishing a confluence wiki.

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:03.000
And that's a lot of the authoring that we do.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.000
But it has challenges.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.000
I think one of the biggest challenges,

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:10.000
especially when you kind of like have notebooks

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
or like really high-value technical content,

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:14.000
they each have their own proprietary format

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:16.000
and it's quite awkward and time-consuming

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:19.000
to take what you've got in a notebook, for example,

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:21.000
and mark down and repurpose it

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:23.000
across many different mediums.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:27.000
These tools typically have

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:29.000
mostly non-existent support

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:32.000
for the kind of technical content that I just talked about.

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.000
They usually don't have any mechanism

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
for including live code in its output.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:39.000
So usually you're ending up copying and pasting.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:41.000
And then when your notebook changes

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:43.000
or your analysis changes,

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:46.000
you've got to hopefully correctly update all your outputs.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:48.000
And that's what I'm just alluding to.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.000
There's no real straightforward way

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:52.000
to sort of automate or reproduce

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.000
computationally derived content.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:57.000
So the idea, I think, is to move to,

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:59.000
and this is really what Jupyter notebooks do

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.000
and what Markdown does,

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.000
move to semantic authoring

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.000
where you don't literally double-click a word

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:07.000
and say, this is bold,

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:09.000
but you sort of write textually,

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:11.000
this is a heading, this is italicized,

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:13.000
this is code, this is a block quote.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:16.000
And then the underlying rendering engine

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:19.000
can give it the right appearance

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:21.000
in a given target format.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:24.000
So again, semantic structure,

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:26.000
really important when we get into talking about

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:29.000
how the system can kind of be hacked and customized.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:31.000
Pandoc parses the document

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.000
into this abstract syntax tree

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:35.000
so the document is something we can actually compute on.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:37.000
We can filter it, we can change it,

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.000
we can amend it,

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:41.000
we can do lots and lots of things to the document

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.000
after it's been parsed into this abstract syntax tree.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:45.000
That is not something you can do, again,

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:47.000
with all these literal output formats.

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:49.000
But here, since we've got the document in this generic form,

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:51.000
it's very easy to compute on.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:53.000
Many of the features of Porto

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:55.000
and many of the extensions that you might want to use or write

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:57.000
take advantage of this fact.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:03.000
Let's talk a little bit about how that works with Jupyter.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:05.000
As we said before,

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:07.000
Jupyter executes cells, creates this Markdown document,

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:09.000
goes into Pandoc.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:11.000
Now, once it's in Pandoc,

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:13.000
it actually,

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:15.000
like I described,

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:17.000
it's an AST.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:19.000
And you can write filters to transform the AST.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:21.000
Again, that's how we implemented

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:23.000
many of the features in Porto,

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:25.000
cross-references, code-folding, layout,

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.000
all kind of computing on this AST.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:29.000
And you can do the same thing.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:31.000
And then the final output gets rendered from the AST.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:33.000
Later on, I've got an example

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:35.000
of doing that with Python.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:37.000
But Pandoc itself,

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:39.000
the power of having your documents

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:41.000
in this generic form

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:43.000
is that it now can create

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:45.000
dozens of formats.

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:47.000
I'm not showing all the formats that Pandoc has.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:49.000
These are some of them.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:51.000
There's the conventional document formats,

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:53.000
presentation formats,

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:55.000
many different varieties of Markdown,

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:57.000
wiki formats,

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:59.000
other formats you may or may not have heard of,

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:01.000
but actually end up being important in different contexts.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:03.000
So it's an incredibly powerful and flexible system.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:05.000
You can even write custom writers

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:07.000
to support systems

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:09.000
that it doesn't itself natively understand.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:11.000
An example of this,

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:13.000
these are some things

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:15.000
that we added to Pandoc.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:17.000
So Hugo,

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:19.000
many of you are familiar with that.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:21.000
It's a very popular tool for building websites.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:23.000
It uses its own version

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:25.000
of Markdown based on a library

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:27.000
called Goldmark.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:29.000
DocuSource is another product

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:31.000
that is used to create also websites.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:33.000
It uses its own flavor of Markdown,

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:35.000
MDX Markdown,

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:37.000
where each Markdown page is actually

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:39.000
an MDX application.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:41.000
Confluence, you've probably heard of,

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:43.000
has its own XML format.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:45.000
I talked about ASCII doc earlier.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:47.000
None of these are actually supported natively by Pandoc,

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:49.000
but we extended Pandoc

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:51.000
to be able to target these.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:53.000
So if your organization uses Hugo

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.000
to publish content and you have a notebook,

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:57.000
you can now,

00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:59.000
with format Hugo,

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:01.000
take that notebook, turn it into Markdown,

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:03.000
and then have it work

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:05.000
within a Hugo website.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:07.000
Similarly with DocuSource,

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:09.000
I've got the same notebook,

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:11.000
and I write MDX Markdown,

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:13.000
which is the formal Markdown understood by DocuSource,

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:15.000
and now my notebook shows up

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:17.000
in the DocuSource website.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.000
Similarly, Confluence.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.000
Lots of organizations use Confluence

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
as a core knowledge management tool.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.000
It'd be great if we could push our notebooks

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:27.000
up into Confluence.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:29.000
We wrote an extension of Pandoc

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:31.000
that takes that AST

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:33.000
and transforms it into native Confluence XML,

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:35.000
so the same notebook now just shows up

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:37.000
as a Confluence page

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:39.000
inside a Confluence wiki.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:41.000
I talked before about

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:43.000
asking Doc to publish

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:45.000
books with O'Reilly.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:47.000
Okay.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:49.000
I want to talk a little bit about

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:51.000
Jupyter notebooks, and I think

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:53.000
people have different opinions about notebooks.

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:55.000
You've probably seen or heard of,

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:57.000
maybe even attended

00:26:57.000 --> 00:26:59.000
Joel Grewe's talk, I Don't Like Notebooks,

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:01.000
from Jupyter's Conf 2018,

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
or Jeremy Howard's response,

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:05.000
I Like Notebooks.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:07.000
A lot of controversy about notebooks,

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:09.000
a lot of hate, a lot of love,

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.000
and I think

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:13.000
the most important thing to recognize

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:15.000
is for all

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:17.000
the things they do well and don't do well,

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:19.000
they are really the corn of the realm.

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:21.000
They define

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:23.000
a standard container

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:25.000
for code output and related narrative

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:27.000
that you can compute on,

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:29.000
and that is really, really powerful.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:31.000
The fact that a notebook

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:33.000
can be published to GitHub,

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:35.000
or it can be published to Colab

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:37.000
and interacted with.

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:39.000
It can be authored by lots of different tools.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:41.000
It's also

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:43.000
a source of content for embedding

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:45.000
other documents.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:47.000
Notebooks are very convenient for a lot of things,

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:49.000
and I think

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:51.000
they're a really important thing to build around

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:53.000
when we think about tools for publishing

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:55.000
data and data science.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:57.000
I talked about

00:27:57.000 --> 00:27:59.000
it as an authoring tool.

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:01.000
It's a REPL with embedded narrative

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:03.000
that's awesome for this idea of thinking

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:05.000
and telling stories with data.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:07.000
Lots of different notebook

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:09.000
authoring tools are available,

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:11.000
and all the file formats

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:13.000
are completely compatible.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:15.000
Now, for those of you

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:17.000
who don't like the idea of authoring

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:19.000
in a big JSON file, that's kind of one of the biggest

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:21.000
complaints about notebooks is,

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.000
wow, how do I diff them?

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:25.000
It's really gross that it's all in a JSON file

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:27.000
and you've just got code.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:29.000
Why is it in this big monolithic JSON file?

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:31.000
You might not know that there's a package

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:33.000
called Jupytext, which actually has

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:35.000
not one, not two,

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:37.000
not three, but ten different

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:39.000
plain text formats to represent notebooks.

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.000
Some based on Markdown,

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:43.000
some based on just

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:45.000
a Python script that has special comments in it.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:47.000
You can still use Jupyter

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:49.000
and Jupyter notebooks, even in

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:51.000
a plain text workflow.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:53.000
Corda has its own variation of that.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:55.000
This is the

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:57.000
QMD, or the pure

00:28:57.000 --> 00:28:59.000
Markdown representation

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:01.000
of the notebook that we've been

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:03.000
showing for the whole talk, the Pong & Penguins notebook.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:05.000
You can see it has

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:07.000
the metadata

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:09.000
options, it has code chunks,

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:11.000
it has Markdown, other code

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:13.000
chunks, cell options, all the

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:15.000
same things you saw in Jupyter, just in a

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:17.000
text file.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:19.000
We have a VS Code extension

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:21.000
you can use, too. It gives you

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:23.000
some of the similar affordances

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:25.000
that you would expect in a notebook, like being able

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:27.000
to run a cell, or run cells above,

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
or run the next cell, or have code

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:31.000
completion, and things like that.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:33.000
I think it's important when we talk about notebooks to think about it

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.000
as kind of an ecosystem,

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.000
a standard container,

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:39.000
and there's lots of different ways to author for them

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:41.000
and work with them

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:43.000
that aren't tied to the traditional

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:45.000
I-V format.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:47.000
There's another scenario

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:49.000
which I think is really interesting, where

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:51.000
you

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:53.000
have a notebook that has a bunch of

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:55.000
computations, and it maybe has the results

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:57.000
of predictions,

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:59.000
or it has figures, or it has tables,

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:01.000
and you want to use that in

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.000
other documents, but still not

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:05.000
lose the connection back to the original notebook.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:07.000
Here's an example of a notebook

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:09.000
that will not actually be published.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:11.000
This notebook will not be the main document

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:13.000
that's published, but rather its outputs

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:15.000
will be embedded in another

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:17.000
document. You can see here this embed

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:19.000
or code.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:21.000
Here's a QMD document.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:23.000
It's got narrative,

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:25.000
and it's got this embed, which says

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:27.000
please embed a cell

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:29.000
from an external notebook right

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.000
here. When you do that, and then

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:33.000
publish it, it retains the

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:35.000
connection to the notebook. You can see,

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:37.000
I've published this document,

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:39.000
but there are source

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:41.000
notebooks behind it that you can link to,

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:43.000
and here you can see for this particular

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:45.000
cell, there's a source

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:47.000
cell for this figure that you can go

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:49.000
look at. Here you may want to,

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:51.000
for decision makers, present a narrative

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:53.000
and figures, but then you want

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:55.000
people to be able to go inspect the code.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:57.000
When you click that link, you end up

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:59.000
navigating into the notebook view,

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.000
and here you can see the code

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.000
and all the narratives in the notebook, or even

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:05.000
download the notebook if you want to

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:07.000
run it and inspect it locally.

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:09.000
We're actually working with

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:11.000
some of those other projects I mentioned

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.000
earlier, JupyterBook, MsJS,

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:15.000
with Sloan

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:17.000
and AGU, kind of trying

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:19.000
to find a standard to let notebooks

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:21.000
be a standard part of the

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:23.000
scientific record. Let them participate

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:25.000
in peer review, don't lose,

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:27.000
preserve them as source materials

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:29.000
all the way through the process, and actually

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:31.000
have the code and the notebooks

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:33.000
be included in archives.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:35.000
We're very excited about that.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:37.000
A little bit to finish

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:39.000
up about how the system

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:41.000
works and how you can customize and hack

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:43.000
the system.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:45.000
A little bit first about how we

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:47.000
interface with Jupyter kernels.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:49.000
We execute code cells using

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:51.000
Jupyter. All Jupyter kernels

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:53.000
are supported. I would say that Python and Julia

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.000
are most widely used,

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:57.000
and they have probably the best tooling,

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.000
but I've seen people use the C

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:01.000
kernel, the Bash kernel, the APL kernel,

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:03.000
the SAS kernel, lots of different

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:05.000
kernels that I've seen

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:07.000
people use with Cordo.

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:09.000
One of the things we do is we want

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:11.000
working with these documents to be very interactive,

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:13.000
so we keep the kernels alive

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:15.000
for up to five minutes across renders

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:17.000
because the startup time can be long, especially

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:19.000
for Julia, it can be like 30 seconds,

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:21.000
so we keep the kernel alive so it's

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:23.000
fast and responsive. It's also

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:25.000
important to note Jupyter is not the only

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:27.000
execution engine we support.

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:29.000
The execution engine

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:31.000
part of Cordo is actually extensible.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:33.000
We support the Knitter engine

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:35.000
for compatibility with our Markdown documents, and we

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.000
can add other engines in the future.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:39.000
All the investment we're making in Markdown

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:41.000
and Pandoc and publishing outputs

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:43.000
works with Jupyter

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:45.000
now, but if there are other interesting execution

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.000
engines that come along in the future, we can plug

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:49.000
into this as well.

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:51.000
In terms of cell execution,

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:53.000
you do want to think about

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:55.000
how expensive it is to render

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:57.000
notebooks or render cells.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:32:59.000
If you author an IPyB,

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:01.000
you can control exactly when execution occurs,

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:03.000
you can cache results in the notebook,

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:05.000
you can rerun all the cells or not rerun

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:07.000
all the cells.

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:09.000
If you author a text mode,

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:11.000
it's going to re-execute all the cells and have you

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.000
render in order, but there are

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.000
a couple, and we'll get into the details on these, there are a couple

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:17.000
of caching strategies available

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:19.000
to make that more reasonable.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:21.000
It's really

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:23.000
use whichever execution

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:25.000
model and caching strategy makes the most sense

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:27.000
for your project. There's a lot of ways to customize it.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:29.000
Filters are a really

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:31.000
important part of the system.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:33.000
Filters essentially are

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:35.000
how we implement all the Porto features.

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.000
The document AST comes

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:39.000
in before it goes for final rendering,

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:41.000
and now the filter gets a hold of it

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:43.000
and it can do anything. It can generate content,

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:45.000
it can remove content, it can amend content,

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:47.000
it can add formatting, remove formatting.

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.000
Lots of different things can be done in filters.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:51.000
I'm going to give you a really simple

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:53.000
Python example here.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:55.000
There's a library called PanFlute.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:57.000
We're rendering a notebook, and we've said,

00:33:57.000 --> 00:33:59.000
please run this filter when you render the notebook.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:01.000
You can see this is the full source

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:03.000
code of the filter, and really

00:34:03.000 --> 00:34:05.000
the main thing that's happening, it's a really trivial

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.000
filter. This is

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:09.000
the only code that really matters here, which is

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:11.000
if you find a header and it's less

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:13.000
than level six, increase it.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:15.000
It's just saying increase all the heading levels by one.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:17.000
Again, a very trivial example,

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:19.000
but you can do very, very powerful

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:21.000
things with filters.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.000
Like all this stuff.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:25.000
Many of the features of Porto are implemented

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:27.000
with filters,

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:29.000
and that's

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:31.000
how we do a lot of the magic that we do.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:33.000
Here's some examples of

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:35.000
third-party filters that have been

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:37.000
created for Porto,

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:39.000
Lightbox for HTML

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:41.000
documents,

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:43.000
a thing for showing proteins and trajectories

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:45.000
with Molestar,

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:47.000
social sharing buttons. Any feature you can

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:49.000
imagine, you can actually build a filter

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:51.000
for it and

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:53.000
extend the system.

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:55.000
Lots of different ways to write filters.

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:57.000
There's two Python libraries,

00:34:57.000 --> 00:34:59.000
one by the creator of Pandoc, and then

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.000
Panfluid, the one I showed, has got

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:03.000
a little bit better API and more batteries included.

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:05.000
Pandoc itself includes an

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:07.000
embedded Lua interpreter, so you can

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:09.000
create very fast zero-dependency filters,

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:11.000
and then you can actually write filters

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:13.000
in any language through JSON

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:15.000
representation of AST.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:19.000
We sort of have an extension

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:21.000
mechanism where you can publish

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:23.000
and reuse not just filters,

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:25.000
but also shortcodes, which are

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:27.000
a special variant of filters that's

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:29.000
like a content-generating macro.

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:31.000
You can build custom formats,

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:33.000
so some of the stuff I showed you before,

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.000
Docosaurus and

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:37.000
Confluence and things were sort of built

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:39.000
using our custom format mechanism.

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:41.000
You can add plugins to reveal JS

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:43.000
and also templates

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:45.000
for different types of projects.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:47.000
Lots and lots of ways to build extensions

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:49.000
and lots of extensions available.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:51.000
We actually have

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:53.000
integration with NBDev,

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:55.000
for those of you who don't know about NBDev,

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.000
it's actually a way of developing

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:59.000
Python packages entirely within

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:01.000
Jupyter, and it

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:03.000
automatically creates

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:05.000
CI

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:07.000
for running your tests.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:09.000
It automatically

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:11.000
gives you the code

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:13.000
to publish your package to

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:15.000
PyPy and

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:17.000
Conda, and also

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:19.000
generates a website containing the documentation

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.000
of your package.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.000
In version 2 of NBDev,

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:25.000
Porto is used to generate

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:27.000
that website.

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:29.000
Because Porto is an open-source command-line tool

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:31.000
and very customizable,

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:33.000
it's very easy

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:35.000
to integrate it with other toolchains

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:37.000
that you might be

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:39.000
working with.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:41.000
That's my talk.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:43.000
Thanks very much.

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:45.000
Hopefully, folks have got some questions.

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:47.000
I'd love to hear them.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:49.000
Thank you.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:36:59.000
I do have a blog in

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:01.000
Hugo, and I use Notebooks quite often.

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:03.000
That sounds really interesting.

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:05.000
It seemed odd to me

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:07.000
that you would put in the metadata

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:09.000
in the Notebook that the output

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:11.000
format is Hugo.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:13.000
It seems that would be a Hugo configuration

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:15.000
thing to say, render...

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.000
In the case of Hugo,

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:19.000
you don't. If you put

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:21.000
a Notebook in a Hugo site,

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:23.000
it just knows to use

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:25.000
the Hugo format.

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:27.000
The project mechanism essentially

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:29.000
creates a format inheritance thing

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:31.000
where it's a Hugo project,

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:33.000
so a Notebook that's not otherwise specified

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:35.000
will render to Hugo.

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:37.000
Does Hugo use Porto by default?

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:39.000
You basically

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:41.000
add it, so you just add

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:43.000
Notebooks to your Hugo, and then you say,

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:45.000
Porto preview or Porto render.

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:47.000
It makes sure that the Notebooks are rendered,

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:49.000
and then Hugo picks them up

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:51.000
and uses them.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:01.000
If we already have a website

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:03.000
that's run on Hugo and

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:05.000
just adds...

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:07.000
You can completely

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:09.000
do that.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:11.000
It'll just go right in there.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:13.000
The graphics and the pictures

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:15.000
and stuff, will it in the static?

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:17.000
It uses a feature

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:19.000
of Hugo called page bundles.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:21.000
Page bundles is where you put

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:23.000
an article or post in its own directory,

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:25.000
and when you put the index.md,

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:27.000
when you do that,

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:29.000
it actually copies the whole directory to static

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:31.000
for you, so you don't have to coordinate

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:33.000
over an asset.

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:39.000
Do you have any features associated

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:41.000
with this process in transclusions?

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:43.000
I don't think so.

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:57.000
I have a question about

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:59.000
which article

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:01.000
formats are supported

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:03.000
on Porto.

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:05.000
Are they mostly the Hyopack

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:07.000
ones, like Nature?

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:09.000
Yeah, so there's a thing.

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:11.000
There's a GitHub portal called Porto

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:13.000
Journals, where we basically created

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.000
a bunch of... We probably got

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:17.000
a dozen or so.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:19.000
I think Nature's

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:21.000
in there. We did five or six

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:23.000
and then the community contributed another six

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:25.000
or seven, and that will grow over time.

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:27.000
It's not difficult

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:29.000
to create your own. A lot of times, users

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:31.000
decide they want to publish to a journal with

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:33.000
Porto, and then they just make the template

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:35.000
based on the journal's

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:37.000
LaTeX template.

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:39.000
So, anyone

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:41.000
you want to be supported can be supported.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:43.000
Some of them are already there, and some of them you have to

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:45.000
make your own template.

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:47.000
Has there

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:49.000
actually been any tool developed

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:51.000
to convert LaTeX

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:53.000
to Porto?

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:55.000
Well, you can... So Pandoc

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:57.000
can read, can parse

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:59.000
LaTeX and create markdowns from it.

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:01.000
It's obviously not going to

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:03.000
be able to take completely

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.000
arbitrary LaTeX and always do the right thing.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:07.000
But for basic things,

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:09.000
basic formatting, tables, headings,

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:11.000
structure,

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:13.000
it can convert, yes,

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:15.000
it can convert LaTeX into a markdown.

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.000
And even

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:19.000
tame, notoriously horrible

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:21.000
LaTeX tables?

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:23.000
Maybe. I don't know. It has

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:25.000
a table parser. The

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:27.000
developers at Pandoc are very

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:29.000
sophisticated about LaTeX, and so

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:31.000
I don't know how good the table parser is, but I know

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:33.000
they work hard at it.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:35.000
All right. Thank you.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.000
Okay. I'm sorry

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:39.000
we're out of time. Let's give a big round of applause

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:41.000
to...

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:43.000
applause

